   "response_text": "The average initial risk attitudes of households remain constant across all time steps, with no observed deviations or shifts in values as steps progress. The data reveals a narrow but diverse distribution of initial risk attitudes, ranging from highly risk-averse values (-0.111) to moderately risk-prone levels (up to 0.182), though the majority cluster between -0.05 and 0.07. These fixed positions across iterations suggest that agent strategies remain stable under homogeneous behavioral configurations, with no apparent adaptation mechanisms operating within the specified parameters. The presence of both positive and negative initial risk attitudes implies varied baseline tendencies toward either gambling with resource allocation or prioritizing conservation, even as climatic variability and social learning conditions are simulated. Notably, the absence of dynamic adjustments to these attitudes throughout the 100 steps indicates that the tested configuration prioritizes static baseline behaviors over adaptive learning processes in this particular simulation setup."
}

